Document: Camera2D
Path: godot/classes/class_camera2d.rst
Summary: This section details the properties of the Camera2D node, including its anchor mode, custom viewport, drag margins, limits, smoothing options, and zoom.

Property Descriptions:
anchor_mode (AnchorMode): The Camera2D's anchor point. Default: 1.
Method: set_anchor_mode(value: AnchorMode)
Method: get_anchor_mode()

custom_viewport (Node): The custom Viewport node attached to the Camera2D. If null or not a Viewport, uses the default viewport instead.
Method: set_custom_viewport(value: Node)
Method: get_custom_viewport()

drag_bottom_margin (float): Bottom margin needed to drag the camera. A value of 1 makes the camera move only when reaching the bottom edge of the screen. Default: 0.2.
Method: set_drag_margin(margin: Side, drag_margin: float)
Method: get_drag_margin(margin: Side)

drag_horizontal_enabled (bool): If true, the camera only moves when reaching the horizontal (left and right) drag margins. If false, the camera moves horizontally regardless of margins. Default: false.
Method: set_drag_horizontal_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_drag_horizontal_enabled()

drag_horizontal_offset (float): The relative horizontal drag offset of the camera between the right (-1) and left (1) drag margins. Note: Used to set the initial horizontal drag offset; determine the current offset; or force the current offset. It's not automatically updated when drag_horizontal_enabled is true or the drag margins are changed. Default: 0.0.
Method: set_drag_horizontal_offset(value: float)
Method: get_drag_horizontal_offset()

drag_left_margin (float): Left margin needed to drag the camera. A value of 1 makes the camera move only when reaching the left edge of the screen. Default: 0.2.
Method: set_drag_margin(margin: Side, drag_margin: float)
Method: get_drag_margin(margin: Side)

drag_right_margin (float): Right margin needed to drag the camera. A value of 1 makes the camera move only when reaching the right edge of the screen. Default: 0.2.
Method: set_drag_margin(margin: Side, drag_margin: float)
Method: get_drag_margin(margin: Side)

drag_top_margin (float): Top margin needed to drag the camera. A value of 1 makes the camera move only when reaching the top edge of the screen. Default: 0.2.
Method: set_drag_margin(margin: Side, drag_margin: float)
Method: get_drag_margin(margin: Side)

drag_vertical_enabled (bool): If true, the camera only moves when reaching the vertical (top and bottom) drag margins. If false, the camera moves vertically regardless of the drag margins. Default: false.
Method: set_drag_vertical_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_drag_vertical_enabled()

drag_vertical_offset (float): The relative vertical drag offset of the camera between the bottom (-1) and top (1) drag margins. Note: Used to set the initial vertical drag offset; determine the current offset; or force the current offset. It's not automatically updated when drag_vertical_enabled is true or the drag margins are changed. Default: 0.0.
Method: set_drag_vertical_offset(value: float)
Method: get_drag_vertical_offset()

editor_draw_drag_margin (bool): If true, draws the camera's drag margin rectangle in the editor. Default: false.
Method: set_margin_drawing_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_margin_drawing_enabled()

editor_draw_limits (bool): If true, draws the camera's limits rectangle in the editor. Default: false.
Method: set_limit_drawing_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_limit_drawing_enabled()

editor_draw_screen (bool): If true, draws the camera's screen rectangle in the editor. Default: true.
Method: set_screen_drawing_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_screen_drawing_enabled()

enabled (bool): Controls whether the camera can be active or not. If true, the Camera2D will become the main camera when it enters the scene tree and there is no active camera currently (see Viewport.get_camera_2d). When the camera is currently active and enabled is set to false, the next enabled Camera2D in the scene tree will become active. Default: true.
Method: set_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_enabled()

ignore_rotation (bool): If true, the camera's rendered view is not affected by its Node2D.rotation and Node2D.global_rotation. Default: true.
Method: set_ignore_rotation(value: bool)
Method: is_ignoring_rotation()

limit_bottom (int): Bottom scroll limit in pixels. The camera stops moving when reaching this value, but offset can push the view past the limit. Default: 10000000.
Method: set_limit(margin: Side, limit: int)
Method: get_limit(margin: Side)

limit_enabled (bool): If true, the limits will be enabled. Disabling this will allow the camera to focus anywhere, when the four limit_* properties will not work. Default: true.
Method: set_limit_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_limit_enabled()

limit_left (int): Left scroll limit in pixels. The camera stops moving when reaching this value, but offset can push the view past the limit. Default: -10000000.
Method: set_limit(margin: Side, limit: int)
Method: get_limit(margin: Side)

limit_right (int): Right scroll limit in pixels. The camera stops moving when reaching this value, but offset can push the view past the limit. Default: 10000000.
Method: set_limit(margin: Side, limit: int)
Method: get_limit(margin: Side)

limit_smoothed (bool): If true, the camera smoothly stops when reaches its limits. This property has no effect if position_smoothing_enabled is false. Note: To immediately update the camera's position to be within limits without smoothing, even with this setting enabled, invoke reset_smoothing(). Default: false.
Method: set_limit_smoothing_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_limit_smoothing_enabled()

limit_top (int): Top scroll limit in pixels. The camera stops moving when reaching this value, but offset can push the view past the limit. Default: -10000000.
Method: set_limit(margin: Side, limit: int)
Method: get_limit(margin: Side)

offset (Vector2): The camera's relative offset. Useful for looking around or camera shake animations. The offsetted camera can go past the limits defined in limit_top, limit_bottom, limit_left and limit_right. Default: Vector2(0, 0).
Method: set_offset(value: Vector2)
Method: get_offset()

position_smoothing_enabled (bool): If true, the camera's view smoothly moves towards its target position at position_smoothing_speed. Default: false.
Method: set_position_smoothing_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_position_smoothing_enabled()

position_smoothing_speed (float): Speed in pixels per second of the camera's smoothing effect when position_smoothing_enabled is true. Default: 5.0.
Method: set_position_smoothing_speed(value: float)
Method: get_position_smoothing_speed()

process_callback (Camera2DProcessCallback): The camera's process callback. Default: 1.
Method: set_process_callback(value: Camera2DProcessCallback)
Method: get_process_callback()

rotation_smoothing_enabled (bool): If true, the camera's view smoothly rotates, via asymptotic smoothing, to align with its target rotation at rotation_smoothing_speed. Note: This property has no effect if ignore_rotation is true. Default: false.
Method: set_rotation_smoothing_enabled(value: bool)
Method: is_rotation_smoothing_enabled()

rotation_smoothing_speed (float): The angular, asymptotic speed of the camera's rotation smoothing effect when rotation_smoothing_enabled is true. Default: 5.0.
Method: set_rotation_smoothing_speed(value: float)
Method: get_rotation_smoothing_speed()

zoom (Vector2): The camera's zoom. Higher values are more zoomed in. For example, a zoom of Vector2(2.0, 2.0) will be twice as zoomed in on each axis (the view covers an area four times smaller). In contrast, a zoom of Vector2(0.5, 0.5) will be twice as zoomed out on each axis (the view covers an area four times larger). The X and Y components should generally always be set to the same value, unless you wish to stretch the camera view. Note: FontFile.oversampling does not take Camera2D zoom into account. This means that zooming in/out will cause bitmap fonts and rasterized (non-MSDF) dynamic fonts to appear blurry or pixelated unless the font is part of a CanvasLayer that makes it ignore camera zoom. To ensure text remains crisp regardless of zoom, you can enable MSDF font rendering by enabling ProjectSettings.gui/theme/default_font_multichannel_signed_distance_field (applies to the default project font only), or enabling Multichannel Signed Distance Field in the import options of a DynamicFont for custom fonts. On system fonts, SystemFont.multichannel_signed_distance_field can be enabled in the inspector. Default: Vector2(1, 1).
Method: set_zoom(value: Vector2)
Method: get_zoom()
---CHUNK---
Document: Camera2D
Path: godot/classes/class_camera2d.rst
Summary: This section describes methods for Camera2D, including alignment, scroll updates, margin and limit management, position and rotation queries, and camera activation.

Method: void align()
Aligns the camera to the tracked node. Note: Calling force_update_scroll() after this method is not required.

Method: void force_update_scroll()
Forces the camera to update scroll immediately.

Method: float get_drag_margin(margin: Side)
Returns the specified Side's margin. See also drag_bottom_margin, drag_top_margin, drag_left_margin, and drag_right_margin.

Method: int get_limit(margin: Side)
Returns the camera limit for the specified Side. See also limit_bottom, limit_top, limit_left, and limit_right.

Method: Vector2 get_screen_center_position()
Returns the center of the screen from this camera's point of view, in global coordinates. Note: The exact targeted position of the camera may be different. See get_target_position().

Method: float get_screen_rotation()
Returns the current screen rotation from this camera's point of view. Note: The screen rotation can be different from Node2D.global_rotation if the camera is rotating smoothly due to rotation_smoothing_enabled.

Method: Vector2 get_target_position()
Returns this camera's target position, in global coordinates. Note: The returned value is not the same as Node2D.global_position, as it is affected by the drag properties. It is also not the same as the current position if position_smoothing_enabled is true (see get_screen_center_position()).

Method: bool is_current()
Returns true if this Camera2D is the active camera (see Viewport.get_camera_2d()).

Method: void make_current()
Forces this Camera2D to become the current active one. enabled must be true.

Method: void reset_smoothing()
Sets the camera's position immediately to its current smoothing destination. This method has no effect if position_smoothing_enabled is false.

Method: void set_drag_margin(margin: Side, drag_margin: float)
Sets the specified Side's margin. See also drag_bottom_margin, drag_top_margin, drag_left_margin, and drag_right_margin.

Method: void set_limit(margin: Side, limit: int)
Sets the camera limit for the specified Side. See also limit_bottom, limit_top, limit_left, and limit_right.